40|$|This article {{summarizes}} {{the emergency department}} approach to diagnosing cerebellar infarction in the patient presenting with vertigo. Vertigo is defined and identification <b>of</b> a <b>vertigo</b> syndrome is discussed. The differentiation <b>of</b> common <b>vertigo</b> syndromes such as benign paroxysmal positional vertigo, Meniere’s disease, migrainous vertigo, and vestibular neuritis is summarized. Confirmation <b>of</b> a peripheral <b>vertigo</b> syndrome substantially lowers the likelihood of cerebellar infarction, as do indicators of a peripheral disorder such as an abnormal head impulse test. Approximately 10 % of patients with cerebellar infarction present with vertigo and no localizing neurologic deficits. The majority of these may have other signs <b>of</b> central <b>vertigo,</b> specifically direction-changing nystagmus and severe ataxia. [West J Emerg Med. 2009; 10 (4) : 273 - 277. ...|$|R
